This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it discusses the performance of the proposed loss function on basic vision tasks such as registration and clustering. Additionally, the paper also discusses the use of the loss function in learning-based tasks such as generative image synthesis and unsupervised monocular depth estimation, which suggests that it could also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper also introduces a probabilistic interpretation of the loss function, which could make it relevant to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) and signal and image processing (cs.SI) sub-categories.
